#Text=Jack
#Text=Black ( rat catcher )
#Text=For other people named Jack Black , see Jack Black ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=Jack Black was a rat-catcher and mole destroyer from Battersea , England during the middle of the nineteenth century . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=Black cut a striking figure in his self-made " uniform " of a green topcoat , scarlet waistcoat , and breeches , with a huge leather sash inset with cast-iron rats .
#Text=Black promoted himself as the Queen 's official rat-catcher , but he never held a royal warrant . [ 2 ]
#Text=Biography

#Text=Jack Black is known particularly through Henry Mayhew 's account in London Labour and the London Poor , where he tells Mayhew of his work and experiences , including a number of occasions when he nearly died from infection following rat bites . [ 1 ]
#Text=Jack Black , circa 1863
#Text=When he caught any unusually coloured rats , he bred them , to establish new colour varieties .
#Text=He would sell his home-bred domesticated coloured rats as pets , mainly , as Black observed , " to well-bred young ladies to keep in squirrel cages " .
#Text=Beatrix Potter is believed to have been one of his customers , and she dedicated the book Samuel Whiskers to her rat of the same name . [ 2 ]
#Text=The more sophisticated ladies of court kept their rats in dainty gilded cages , and even Queen Victoria herself kept a rat or two .
#Text=It was in this way that domesticated — or fancy — rats were established .
#Text=Black also supplied live rats for rat-baiting in pits , a popular mid- Victorian pastime . [ 2 ]
#Text=Black had a number of sidelines beyond rats , including fishing ( for food and supplying aquaria ) , bird catching and taxidermy . [ 1 ]
#Text=He was also an accomplished dog breeder .
#Text=He told Mayhew : " I had a little rat dog — a black tan terrier of the name of Billy — which was the greatest stock dog in London of that day .

#Text=Her black and white hooded Rattus norvegicus won  Best in Show , " and the Rat Fancy was formally launched .

column1: #Text=The original Rat Fancy lasted until 1931 , as part of the National Mouse and Rat Club .
#Text=The modern Rat Fancy was revived in 1976 with the formation of the National Fancy Rat Society , and the fancy rat spread around the world .
#Text=Nowadays , fancy rats are widely accepted as pets and exhibition animals .
#Text=Pop culture
#Text=Your Friend the Rat , a Pixar short film which briefly mentions Black in the history of rats . [ 4 ]
